panels.description:
This information comes from DLT log file by filtering the message with SMAP as context ID.

PSS is the private memory used by that process plus the proportion of memory used with other processes.
Example:
 - Process A has 30 MB of unshared memory
 - Process B has 70 MB of unshared memory
 - Both process have 50% of the same shared memory, 80 MB

In this case the 80 MB of shared memory will be divided equal to both processes, so the PSS will be:
 - Process A -> 30 MB + ( 80 MB / 2) = 70 MB
 - Process B -> 70 MB + ( 80 MB / 2) = 110 MB

targets.query: SELECT /^process_.*/ FROM "node0_mem_pss" WHERE ("job" =~ /^$job_name$/) AND ("build" =~ /^$build_id$/) AND ("testcase" =~/^.*${testcase}.*$/) AND ("hardware_revision" =~ /^$hardware_revision$/) AND $timeFilter
SELECT ("value"), "testcase" FROM "cpu_load"WHERE "testcase" != 'None' AND $timeFilter AND ("build" =~ /^$build_id$/) AND ("hardware_revision" =~ /^$hardware_revision$/) GROUP BY "testcase"

SELECT /^process_.*/, testcase FROM "node0_mem_pss" WHERE ("job" =~ /^$job_name$/) AND ("build" =~ /^$build_id$/) AND ("testcase" =~/^.*${testcase}.*$/) AND ("hardware_revision" =~ /^$hardware_revision$/) AND $timeFilter GROUP BY "testcase"

panels.title: Node0 - Mem PSS by process

panels.description:
This information comes from DLT log file by filtering the message with SMAP as context ID.

RSS is the private memory used by that process plus the memory used with other processes.
Example:
 - Process A has 30 MB of unshared memory
 - Process B has 70 MB of unshared memory
 - Both process have 80 MB of shared memory

In this case the 80 MB of shared memory will sum with the private memory used in both processes, so the RSS will be:
 - Process A -> 30 MB + 80 MB = 110 MB
 - Process B -> 70 MB + 80 MB = 150 MB

Since the RSS will sum the shared memory with the private memory instead of the proportion of shared memory can be misleading, but it can be used to have an ideia of how much memory each process is using
